  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Innovation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Traditional businesses (restaurants, retail, basic consulting) are routinely rejected. The panel wants genuine innovation and scalability. If your business could exist in 1990, it's probably not innovative enough for Startup Denmark.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Weak Danish Connection</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your application should explain why Denmark specifically—not just "I want to live in Copenhagen." Show Danish market relevance, partnerships, or ecosystem benefits. Generic applications suggesting any EU country would work get skeptical reviews.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring the 75-Cap Competition</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Only 75 permits per year means stiff competition. Your application competes against other entrepreneurs globally. Submit early in the year if possible, and make your innovation case compelling.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Planning Side Income</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your permit only allows work in your approved startup—no freelancing, consulting, or employment on the side without a separate permit. If you need income flexibility, consider other countries.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Copenhagen Housing</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Copenhagen housing market is brutal. Finding an apartment can take months. Don't arrive assuming you'll quickly find somewhere to live. Budget for expensive short-term rentals or hotels initially.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Denmark -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Denmark</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Denmark has universal healthcare funded through taxes. After getting your CPR number, you receive a yellow health card (sundhedskort) giving access to free healthcare services.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Access</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">After CPR Registration</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP visits: Free</li>
          <li>✓ Specialists: Free (with referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care: Free</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health: Covered (with referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity: Fully covered</li>
          <li>✓ Prescriptions: Partially subsidized</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Not Covered / Pay Privately</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>△ Adult dental care</li>
          <li>△ Glasses/contact lenses</li>
          <li>△ Physiotherapy (mostly)</li>
          <li>△ Private hospital rooms</li>
          <li>△ Cosmetic procedures</li>
          <li>△ Some prescriptions (partial cost)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Danish Healthcare Works</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      You choose a GP (praktiserende læge) from your local area. Your GP is the gatekeeper—referrals needed for specialists. Wait times exist but are generally reasonable. Emergency care (skadestue) is always available.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Private supplement:</strong> Many Danes have private health insurance (sundhedsforsikring) through employers or personal policies (€30-80/month). This provides faster access to private hospitals and specialists, plus dental coverage.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How competitive is Startup Denmark?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Very competitive—only 75 permits per year for applicants worldwide. You need a genuinely innovative, scalable business concept. Traditional businesses are routinely rejected. Strong applications with clear innovation stories have the best chances.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I do freelance work on the side?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No—your permit only allows work in your approved startup business. Freelancing, consulting, or employment require separate permits. This is stricter than many other countries' startup visas. Plan your income accordingly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You must maintain your approved business activity to keep your permit. If the business fails, you need to either start a new approved business or leave Denmark. There's no safety net to stay without active business operations.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How difficult is finding housing in Copenhagen?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Extremely difficult. Official waiting lists can be 10+ years. Most newcomers use Facebook groups, BoligPortal, or short-term rentals. Expect to pay high prices and potentially live outside central Copenhagen initially. Start searching before arrival.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Danish?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not legally required—Copenhagen's business environment operates largely in English. However, Danish helps with daily life, integration, and long-term residency. Many expats survive on English alone, but learning Danish demonstrates commitment and opens doors.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After sufficient years of legal residence (typically 4-8 years depending on circumstances), you can apply for permanent residence. Requirements include Danish language test, employment/self-employment, and integration criteria. Startup Denmark time counts toward this.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Startup Denmark is an exclusive programme for genuinely innovative entrepreneurs—not a pathway for freelancers or traditional businesses. The 75 annual permit cap makes it highly competitive. You need a scalable, innovative concept that the Danish Business Authority's expert panel will approve.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For those who qualify, Denmark offers exceptional quality of life: excellent work-life balance, comprehensive social benefits, world-class healthcare, and a strong startup ecosystem. Copenhagen's fintech, cleantech, and design scenes attract global talent.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The trade-offs are real: high living costs (among the world's highest), difficult housing market, dark winters, and a permit that restricts you to only your approved business. If you need income flexibility or don't have a genuinely innovative concept, consider Germany's freelancer visa or Portugal's DNV instead.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Startup Denmark is for serious innovators who can compete for 75 annual spots with genuinely scalable ideas. Budget €130-300/month for health insurance during the 1-3 month transition to Denmark's excellent (and free) public healthcare system. The high costs and strict requirements filter for committed entrepreneurs.
      </p>
